  • Conclusions

Introduction¶

The aim of this project was to analyse The Movie Database (TMDb) movie dataset which was originally sourced from Kaggle and has been cleaned and provided by Udacity for the 'Investigate a Dataset' Project as part of the Data Analyst Nanodegree. The TMDb dataset collects information about over 10,000 movies from the years 1960 to 2015 and includes columns such as popularity, budget, revenue, cast, director genre, production companies, release date, vote count, vote average, and budget and revenue adjusted for inflation. As noted in the TMDb dataset overview and notes provided by Udacity, there are some odd characters in the 'cast' column which do not need to be cleaned therefore this column's data has been left in its original state. Additionally, the dataset notes highlight that the final two columns for budget and revenue ending in 'adj' contain the budget and revenue of associated movies in terms of 2010 dollars accounting for inflation over time.

This report intends to effectively answer the following questions:

  1. What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have high revenues?
  2. What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have highest popularity scores?
  3. What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have highest voting scores?
  4. Have movie budgets increased over time?
  5. Have movie revenues increased over time?
  6. Has the popularity score and average rating for movies increased over time?
  7. What are the most popular genres from 1960-2015?

This report will demonstrate the overall data analysis process and the accompanying Python code used to answer the aforementioned questions and provide justification for the decisions made throughout the analysis. It is important to note that inferential statistics and machine learning are beyond the scope of this course therefore findings and conclusions drawn in this report are tentative.

Data Attributes¶

Below is a table containing the name of the column and its description;

Column Name Description
id Unique identification number given to each row in the dataset
imdb_id Unique identification number given to each row in the imdb dataset
popularity The popularity score for the movie calculated using a variety of metrics*
budget The original budget spent on the movie in dollars
revenue The original revenue made from the movie in dollars
original_title The original title of the movie
cast The main cast starring in the film
homepage The movie's website homepage
director The director of the film
tagline The movie's tagline
keywords Keywords which relate to the associated movie
overview The movie's synopsis
runtime The length of the movie in minutes
genres The genres which the movie falls under
production_companies The production companies involved in making the movie
release_date When the movie was originally released
vote_count The number of votes cast regarding the rating of the movie
vote_average The average score the movie was voted
release_year The original year in which the movie was released
budget_adj The budget spent on the movie which has been adjusted in terms of 2010 dollars accounting for inflation over time
revenue_adj The revenue made from the movie which has been adjusted in terms of 2010 dollars accounting for inflation over time

*popularity is calculated using a variety of metrics as listed here: https://developers.themoviedb.org/3/getting-started/popularity

Data Cleaning¶

This stage in the data wrangling process will involve dropping unnecessary rows and columns which are not relevant to answering the questions posed at the beginning of this process. It will go on to clean duplicates and null values.

Dropping Unnecessary Columns¶

In this section, the columns which are not relevant to answering our questions will be dropped. Budget and revenue are dropped so that the adjusted values can be employed in our investigation as these are more meaningful when comparing movies from the earliest years in our dataset (1960s) to more recent years.

Handling Missing Values¶

As shown below, there are zero values for budget_adj, revenue_adj as well as runtime. It is assumed that these are infact missing values and should be nulls instead of zeros as movies will always have a budget associated and a runtime of over 0 minutes. This is a point in the analysis process where it is important to decide whether to drop these associated rows, replace the zeros with nulls, or replace the zeros with the mean. After investigating the number of rows that are affected by zero values it doesn't make sense to drop these rows. Additionally, the budget_adj and revenue_adj are of interest and are relevant to our questions posed initially therefore it is decided that to rectify the number of zero values we will replacing the zeros with nulls. This decision was made so that the data wasn't distorted and misleading.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Now that our data has been wrangled, the next stage of the data analysis process is to conduct exploratory data analysis by computing statistics and creating visualisations with the goal of addressing the research questions posed at the beginning of this process.

First we will look at the histograms and scatterplots for each of our columns with quantitative data to gain a better understanding of the distribution.

In [30]:

What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have high revenues?¶

The first question in the investigation is concerned with what kinds of properties are associated with movies that have high revenues. In order to gain a better understanding of possible correlations a series of scatterplots are created.

In [51]:
#scatter plot of budget_adj against revenue_adj with vote_average
plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
sns.scatterplot(x='revenue_adj', y='budget_adj', data=df, hue='vote_average')
plt.title("Revenue vs. Budget (both adjusted for inflation)", fontsize=14)
plt.xlabel("Revenue (adjusted for inflation)")
plt.ylabel("Budget (adjusted for inflation)");

As shown from the graph above budget and revenue are positively correlated. Vote average is also included in the graph to illustrate the budget and revenue of the highest scoring movies. Next the revenue against popularity will be investigated.

Conclusion¶

From the above scatter plots it is evident that there evidence of a positive correlation between the budget and revenue (adjusted for inflation). Additionally there is a very weak positive correlation between revenue and popularity score. From the scatterplot, it is clear that there is no significant correlation between runtime and revenue. Finally, the scatterplot between revenue and average vote rating shows that movies that made more revenue have received a high average vote however a significant number of movies with less revenue also received a high average vote rating.

Have movie budgets increased over time?¶

Next it was of interest to examine movie budgets adjusted over time.

In [59]:
# plotting line graph of average budgets over time

plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
bud_adj_line = df.groupby('release_year')['budget_adj'].mean()
plt.plot(bud_adj_line)
plt.title('Average Budgets (adjusted) over Time', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Years', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Average Budget (adjusted)', fontsize=12);

Conclusions¶

From the above line graph it is evident that average budget (adjusted) was relatively high with significant variance between 1960-1970s and then decreased significantly after 1970s and then started to rise again. From the graph it is evident that average budget peaked in the late 1990s and then has started to decrease again from 2000s-2010s. It is important to note that a significant number of the films in this dataset have null values and therefore this is merely an indication of this dataset and may not hold true for a larger dataset with more budget data.

Have movie revenues increased over time?¶

After examining the budgets over time, the next step was to consider the trend in average revenues (adjusted).

In [45]:
# plotting line graph of  average revenues over time
plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
revenue_adj_l = df.groupby('release_year')['revenue_adj'].mean()
plt.plot(revenue_adj_l)
plt.title(' Average Revenues (adjusted) over Time', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Years', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Average Revenue (adjusted)', fontsize=12);

Conclusion¶

From the above graph it can be seen that average revenue (adjusted for inflation) has fallen overtime, this may be due to the higher number of more recent films in this dataset which may be dragging down the average value for movies after 1980s as from the summary statistics the median release year is 2006. Again it is important to note that there are a significant number of nulls in this dataset and this may not be an accurate reflection of average revenues for movies from 1960-2015. To get a better indication of how revenues and budgets compare over time these will be plotted on the same graph.

In [74]:
revenue_adj_l = df.groupby('release_year')['revenue_adj'].mean()
bud_adj_line = df.groupby('release_year')['budget_adj'].mean()
plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
plt.plot(revenue_adj_l, marker='', color='skyblue', linewidth=2, label = 'revenue')
plt.plot(bud_adj_line, marker='', color='purple', linewidth=2, linestyle='dashed', label='budget')
plt.title(' Average Adjusted Revenues and Budgets over Time', fontsize=14)
plt.xlabel('Years', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Average Value (adjusted)', fontsize=12);
plt.legend();

If we compare the average movie revenues and budgets (adjusted) on the same graph we can see that although average revenues have fallen over time, the average movie revenue remains higher than the budgets therefore on average profits are still being made.

Conclusions¶

At the beginning of this analysis the following questions were considered:

  1. What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have high revenues?
  2. What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have highest popularity scores?
  3. What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have highest voting scores?
  4. Have movie budgets increased over time?
  5. Have movie revenues increased over time?
  6. Has the popularity score and average rating for movies increased over time?
  7. What are the most popular genres from 1960-2015?

After wrangling the data and conducting exploratory data analysis the following conclusions can be drawn, however it is important to note the caveat that these conclusions are based on a small dataset which has a significant value of nulls for budget and revenue adjusted for inflation data and that no statistical tests were conducted therefore these findings are merely indications and are very tentative:

  1. What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have high revenues?

    • Revenue and budget have a weak positive correlation suggesting that the more budget spent on a film tends to make more revenue
    • There is a very weak correlation between revenue and popularity
    • Runtime and revenue do not seem to be correlated and most movies have a runtime of between 100-200 minutes
    • There is a very weak correlation between average vote rating and revenue
  1. What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have highest popularity scores?
    • There is a weak positive correlation between budget and popularity and revenue and popularity
    • Runtime and popularity do not seem to be correlated
  1. What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have highest average voting scores?
    • Average voting rating is positively correlated with budget, revenue, popularity and also vote count
  1. Have movie budgets increased over time?
    • Movie budgets have fluctuated overtime and peaked in the late 1990s. However it is important to note that this is only true for the movies in this dataset and a significant number of movie budgets are nulls.
  1. Have movie revenues increased over time?
    • Movie revenues began to fall after the late 1970s and have remained constant from after 1980s to the 2010s
  1. Has the popularity score and vote average for movies increased over time?
    • Popularity score is increased for movies with a more recent release year however vote average for movies with a more recent release year has declined
  1. What are the most widely produced genres from 1960-2015 ?
    • The top 4 movie genres are drama, comedy, thriller and action
